Add a new test method to a test file: $ARGUMENTS

The argument format is: `<test_file_path> "<scenario description>"`

Example:
```
/add-test-case {{ tests_output }}/test_fleet.py "driver with expired licence should return 403"
```

## Project structure

- Test files: `{{ tests_output }}/test_{tag}.py`
- Each test class corresponds to one API endpoint (the class docstring names it)
- Factory helpers for building response objects: `{{ tests_output }}/conftest.py`
{% if has_services %}
- Fixtures available in every test class:
  - `client_with_mock` — TestClient with the service dependency overridden
  - `mock_service` — `AsyncMock(spec={Tag}Service)` wired into that client
{% endif %}

## Error handling convention

{% if not_found_exception %}
Not-found errors in this project: `{{ not_found_exception }}`
{% else %}
Not-found errors: configure with `mock_service.{method}.side_effect = <NotFoundError>`
{% endif %}

## Steps

1. Parse `$ARGUMENTS` to get the test file path and scenario description
2. Read the test file and identify which test class covers the relevant endpoint
3. Read existing test methods in that class to understand the fixture and assertion pattern
4. Add a new test method:
   - Name: `test_<snake_case_scenario>` (e.g., `test_driver_with_expired_licence_returns_403`)
   - Mirror the fixture signature of other methods in the class
{% if has_services %}
   - Error scenarios (4xx): set `mock_service.{method}.side_effect = <exception>`, call via `client_with_mock`
   - Success scenarios (2xx): set `mock_service.{method}.return_value = <factory_result>`, call via `client_with_mock`
{% endif %}
5. Run the new test to verify it passes:
   ```
   uv run pytest <test_file_path> -k <test_method_name> -v
   ```
6. Fix any failures before finishing
